[test input.it]
# gen189 (basic-chat cat.0), Italian probe. Non-linguistic input carries NO
# language, so the very same classifier serves every language through the same
# code path — the bilingual ratchet by construction (PRINCIPLES.md). The noise
# inputs are identical (punctuation/number/mash are language-invariant); only the
# real-language guard differs, proving Italian prose still passes through the
# classifier to the reasoning core rather than being mistaken for noise.

> ?
< That's just punctuation, not words — what would you like to ask?
> !@#$%^&*()
< That's just punctuation, not words — what would you like to ask?
> 1234567890
< That's just the number 1234567890 with nothing to do — what would you like me to do with it?
> asdfghjkl
< That doesn't look like words to me — did a key get stuck? I'm here when you'd like to ask something.
> aaaaaaaaaa
< That doesn't look like words to me — did a key get stuck? I'm here when you'd like to ask something.

# Guard: an Italian self-question reaches the self-model untouched.
# gen335 (KB-first): identity responses localize via current_language.
> chi sei
< Mi chiamo parrot0.
